ğŸ§  What is a Linked List?
Unlike arrays, a Linked List doesn't use contiguous memory.
Each element (called a node) holds a value and a reference to the next node.
Perfect for insertions and deletions when dynamic memory usage is a priority! ğŸ”

ğŸ’¡ JavaScript Implementation
js
Copy
Edit
class Node {
  constructor(value) {
    this.value = value;
    this.next = null;
  }
}

class LinkedList {
  constructor() {
    this.head = null;
    this.size = 0;
  }

  isEmpty() {
    return this.size === 0;
  }

  getSize() {
    return this.size;
  }

  prepend(value) {
    const node = new Node(value);
    node.next = this.head;
    this.head = node;
    this.size++;
  }

  print() {
    let current = this.head;
    while (current) {
      console.log(current.value);
      current = current.next;
    }
  }
}

// Usage
const list = new LinkedList();
console.log('List is empty:', list.isEmpty());
console.log('List size:', list.getSize());

list.prepend(10);
list.prepend(20);

console.log('After adding elements:');
list.print();
â± Time Complexity
Operation	Time Complexity
prepend()	O(1)
isEmpty()	O(1)
getSize()	O(1)
print()	O(n)
Since prepend directly attaches the new node to the front, it's super fast â€” constant time!
Traversals like print() naturally scale with the number of elements.

ğŸ“š Why use Linked Lists?
âœ… Great for insertion/removal at the beginning
âœ… Avoids shifting elements like arrays
âœ… Ideal when size is not fixed

